access with authorization2star  aThese highly personal essays from a range of academic settings explore the palpable moments of discomfort, disempowerment, and/or enlightenment that emerge when we discard the fiction that the teacher has no body. Visible and/or invisible, the body can transform both the teacher's experience and classroom dynamics. When students think the teacher's body is clearly marked by ethnicity, race, disability, size, gender, sexuality, illness, age, pregnancy, class, linguistic and geographic origins, or some combination of these, both the mode and the content of education can change. Other, less visible aspects of a teacher's body, such as depression or a history of sexual assault, can have an equally powerful impact on how we teach and learn. The collection anatomizes these moments of embodied pedagogy as unexpected teaching opportunities and examines their apparent impact on teacher-student educational dynamics of power, authority, desire, friendship, open-mindedness, and resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCollege teachingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTeacher-student relationshipszUnited States. 0aTeachers with disabilitieszUnited StatesxPsychology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrueggemann, Brenda Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Cortney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiPalma, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Betty Smith, econtribu